# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crankcase-ventilation-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/air-pollution] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] Haagen-Smit was born December 22, 1900, in the Dutch city of Utrecht.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] His father worked as a chemist at the Dutch mint.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] Haagen-Smit attended the *Rijks Hogere Burgerschool* in Utrecht.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He graduated from the University of Utrecht in 1922 with a major in organic chemistry and a minor in mathematics.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He earned his M.A. degree in 1926 and Ph.D. in 1929.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] His work was on terpenes, a hydrocarbon found in plants.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] His dissertation is titled "Investigations in the Field of Sesquiterpenes".
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He stayed at the University of Utrecht from 1929 to 1935 as chief assistant.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He became an expert in plant derived chemicals, particularly Auxins, a hormone.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He was invited to lecture at Harvard University in 1936 by Kenneth Thimann.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He was appointed as associate professor by California Institute of Technology in 1937 by Thomas Hunt Morgan, and professor in 1940, becoming one of the "Dutch Mafia" at Caltech.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] (Another member of the "mafia" was Frits Warmolt Went.) Haagen-Smit studied the flavor of pineapples.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He published a paper jointly with two other scientists on traumatic acid, a wound healing hormone, in *Science* in 1939.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He was the director of the Plant Environmental Laboratory at the California Institute of Technology from 1965 to 1971.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] He started his air pollution research in 1948, when Southern California residents suffered stinging eyes and respiratory irritation from smog.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] His original interest stemmed from damage to crop plants smog was causing in the Los Angeles Basin, and he had received many requests from government agencies to investigate air pollution.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] Using techniques originally developed in his work on the biosynthesis of essential oils, Haagen-Smit showed that smog primarily resulted from a photochemical reaction of the unburned hydrocarbons, ozone, and nitrogen oxides from automobile exhaust and industrial fuel combustion.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] After a representative of the Stanford Research Institute (which was funded by the oil industry) went to Caltech and attempted to discredit Haagen-Smit's findings, Haagen-Smit increased his research efforts.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] By the mid 1950s, the connection between automobiles and smog in Los Angeles became widely accepted in scientific circles.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] Haagen-Smit worked with Arnold Beckman, who developed various equipment for monitoring smog.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] Haagen-Smit's research led the automobile industry to install positive crankcase ventilation, the first vehicle emissions control system, in 1961.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] In 1968 Haagen-Smit was appointed the first Chairman of the California Air Resources Board by Ronald Reagan, California's Governor at the time.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] In 1930, he married Petronella Francina Pennings.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] They had a son, Jan Willem Adrianus, who was born only three months before Petronella died in 1933.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] On June 10, 1935, he married Maria "Zus" Wilhelmina Bloemers, a graduate student of botany in the University of Utrecht.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/arie-jan-haagen-smit] They had three daughters: Maria van Pelt, Maria Daniel, and Joanne Demers.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The **Automobile Manufacturers Association** was a trade group of automobile manufacturers that operated under various names in the United States from 1911 to 1999.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] It was replaced by the Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] A different group called the Automobile Manufacturers' Association was active in the very early 1900s, but then dissolved.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Another early group was the Association of Licensed Automobile Manufacturers, formed in 1903 and which was involved in licensing and collecting royalties from the George Baldwin Selden engine patent.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Henry Ford effectively defeated the patent in court in 1911 and the Association of Licensed Automobile Manufacturers dissolved.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] However, the same manufacturers regrouped later in 1911 and formed the **Automobile Board of Trade**.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In 1913, this became the **National Automobile Chamber of Commerce**.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In 1934, this group renamed itself to the Automobile Manufacturers Association.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] This was the name the group had the longest and became the best known by.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] It focused upon establishing a code for fair competition.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In 1939, it moved its headquarters from New York City, where it had been close to bankers, to Detroit, where the manufacturers were all based.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The organization had a budget of $1 million at the time.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In the 1930s, they promoted disputed information that blamed pedestrians for fatal car wrecks.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The Automobile Manufacturers Association sponsored the Automotive Golden Jubilee, a series of events that lasted ten days.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] It celebrated Detroit as the "Automobile Capital of the World" and the over 90 million automobiles that were made in the first 50 years of the industry.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The festivities were organized by William S.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Knudsen, former president of General Motors, and George W.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Romney, of the AMA who became president of Nash-Kelvinator.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The Jubilee culminated by bringing together fourteen living automotive pioneers.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Charles Brady King - A pioneer credited with being the first person to design, build, and drive a self-propelled automobile on the streets of Detroit in 1896, several months before Henry Ford.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] He also mentored other industry figures, including Henry Ford and Ransom Olds.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] George Holley - Established a company with his brother Earl to supply carburetors for many Detroit-built automobiles, and later produced automotive performance components.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] John Van Benschoten - An automobile dealer.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] During the early stages of World War II, the association played a role in adapting American automotive manufacturing capabilities towards arms production efforts, especially regarding large aircraft engines.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Within hours of the December 7, 1941 attack on Pearl Harbor, the association invited all companies in the larger automotive industry, regardless of whether they were association members, to join a new cooperative undertaking, the Automotive Council for War Production.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] About 654 manufacturing companies joined that produced nearly $29 billion in output, including large numbers of motorized vehicles, tanks, engines, and other products for the Allied military forces.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Between a fifth and a quarter of all U.S. wartime production was accounted for by the automotive industry.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In 1950, the association published the book, *Freedom's Arsenal: The Story of the Automotive Council for War Production*, to document this achievement.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] They promoted the use of the word *accident* to describe car wrecks, as a way to make vehicle-related deaths and injuries seem like an unavoidable matter of fate, rather than a problem that could be addressed.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The automobile industry accomplished this by writing customized articles as a free service for newspapers, using the industry's preferred language.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Following the 1955 Le Mans disaster and the 1957 NASCAR Mercury Meteor crashes into the grandstands, the Automobile Manufacturers Association placed a ban on factory-supported racing.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] As a result, the automotive industry essentially disappeared from NASCAR.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] This ban also extended to manufacturers supplying the pace car for the Indianapolis 500 (leaving local dealerships and track officials to procure vehicles for official use).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The ban began to end in 1962 when Henry Ford II announced that the Ford Motor Company would again begin participating openly in NASCAR.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In 1969, the association engaged with rising federal regulation, including environmental regulation as smog, lead pollution, and other pollutants from the burgeoning automotive industry grew.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] Mann's annual address to the association in 1969, entitled "Clean Air and the Automobile," detailed the industry's attempts to reduce pollutants while questioning the harm caused by them.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The speech is also an early example of industry questioning the risk of global warming brought about by carbon dioxide pollution.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In August 1972, the group changed its name to the **Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association**, to reflect the growing importance of truck makers.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] A major issue then developed over whether foreign-owned automakers with operations and in some cases manufacturing within the U.S. could join the group.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In 1986 the association ruled that foreign transplants had to manufacture half their American sales within the country in order to join; a grandfather clause allowed Honda and Volvo to stay in.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In May 1988, Toyota's attempt to join was rejected on this line.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] By 1992, Toyota and Nissan were able to meet the membership mark and qualify to join.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] In late 1992, the group expelled Honda, Volvo, and heavy truck makers and changed its name to the **American Automobile Manufacturers Association**.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The association now was back to its traditional stance of representing the "Big Three" manufacturers.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] They also moved their headquarters from Detroit to Washington, D.C., in order to have a stronger governmental presence.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] However, their situation became problematic with the DaimlerChrysler merger of 1998, which meant there were only two American-only manufacturers, too few for an organization.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/automobile-manufacturers-association] The American Automobile Manufacturers Association was thus phased out in January 1999, and a new and different successor group, the Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers, was formed and included many foreign-owned manufacturers.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] A **crankcase ventilation system** (**CVS**) removes unwanted gases from the crankcase of an internal combustion engine.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The system usually consists of a tube, a one-way valve and a vacuum source (such as the inlet manifold).
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The unwanted gases, called *blow-by*, are gases from the combustion chamber which have leaked past the piston rings.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Early engines released these gases to the atmosphere simply by leaking them through the crankcase seals.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The first specific crankcase ventilation system was the *road draught tube*, which used a partial vacuum to draw the gases through a tube and release them to the atmosphere.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Positive crankcase ventilation (PCV) systems – first used in the Second World War and present on most modern engines – send the crankcase gases back to the combustion chamber, as part of the vehicle emissions control, in order to reduce air pollution.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Two-stroke engines with a crankcase compression design do not need a crankcase ventilation system, because normal operation of the engine involves sending the crankcase gases to the combustion chamber.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Until the early 20th century, blow-by gases escaped from the crankcase by leaking through seals and gaskets.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] It was considered normal for oil to leak from an engine and drip onto the ground, as this had also been the case for steam engines in the decades before.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Gaskets and shaft seals were intended to limit the leakage of oil, but they were usually not expected to entirely prevent it.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The blow-by gases would diffuse through the oil and then leak through the seals and gaskets into the atmosphere, causing air pollution and odors.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The first refinement in crankcase ventilation was the *road draught tube*.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This is a pipe running from the crankcase (or the valve cover on an overhead-valve engine) down to a downwards-facing open end located in the vehicle's slipstream.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] When the vehicle is moving, airflow across the open end of the tube creates suction (a draught) that pulls gases out of the crankcase.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] To prevent too much vacuum being created, the blow-by gases are replaced by fresh air using a device called a *breather*.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The breather is often located in the oil cap.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Many breathers had a cup or scoop and were located in the air stream of the engine radiator fan.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This type of system is the *pressure–suction* type; air is forced into the scoop of the breather and by vacuum is drawn out by the road draft tube.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Another variation of the pressure–suction type was used on VW Porsche air-cooled engines whereby the front crankcase pulley has a reverse screw built into it which brings air into the engine and air escapes the crankcase with the road draft tube.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This system works very well in getting rid of crankcase vapors which are harmful to the engine.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] As per the earlier engines, the road draught tube system also created pollution and objectionable odors.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The draught tube could become clogged with snow or ice, in which case crankcase pressure would build and cause oil leaks and gasket failure.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] On slow-moving delivery vehicles and boats, there was often no suitable air slipstream for the road draught tube.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] In these situations, the engines used positive pressure at the breather tube to push blow-by gases from the crankcase.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Therefore, the breather air intake was often located in the airflow behind the engine's cooling fan.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The crankcase gases exited to the atmosphere via a draught tube.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Although the modern purpose of a positive crankcase ventilation (**PCV**) system is to reduce air pollution, the original purpose was to allow an engine to operate underwater without the water leaking in.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The first PCV systems were built during World War II, to allow tank engines to operate during deep fording operations, where the normal draught tube ventilator would have allowed water to enter the crankcase and destroy the engine.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] In the early 1950s, Professor Arie Jan Haagen-Smit established that pollution from automobile engines was a major cause of the smog crisis being experienced in Los Angeles, California.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The California *Motor Vehicle Pollution Control Board* (a precursor to the California Air Resources Board) was established in 1960 and began researching how to prevent blow-by gases from being released directly into the atmosphere.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The PCV system was designed to re-circulate the gases into the air intake so that they could be combined with the fresh air/fuel and get more completely combusted.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] In 1961, California regulations required that all new cars be sold with a PCV system, therefore representing the first implementation of a vehicle emissions control device.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Starting with the 1963 model year, most new cars sold in the U.S. were so equipped by voluntary industry action so as to avoid having to make multiple state-specific versions of vehicles.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] PCV quickly became standard equipment on all vehicles worldwide because of its benefits not only in emissions reduction but also in engine internal cleanliness and oil lifespan.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] After eighteen months of investigation, the grand jury returned a "no-bill" decision, clearing the AMA, but resulting in a consent decree that all U.S. automobile companies agreed not to work jointly on smog control activities for a period of ten years.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] In the decades since, legislation and regulation of vehicular emissions has tightened substantially.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Most of today's gasoline engines continue to use PCV systems.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] In order for the PCV system to draw fumes out of the crankcase, the system must have a source of fresh air.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The source of this fresh air is the "crankcase breather", which is usually ducted from the engine's air filter or intake manifold.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The breather is usually provided with baffles and filters to prevent oil mist and vapour from fouling the air filter.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This phenomenon can be further reduced by installing after-market air oil separators or catch cans, as colloquially known, to pull oil mist out of suspension and collect it in a reservoir before it can reach the intake.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] A properly designed crankcase breather will also be designed in a manner that promotes the scavenging effect, or the creation of suction within the crankcase breather to further aid in the removal of blow-by gases.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] It is this effect that keeps the crankcase at slightly negative pressure when a properly functioning PCV system is in place.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Intake manifold vacuum is applied to the crankcase via the PCV valve.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The airflow through the crankcase and engine interior sweeps away combustion byproduct gases.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This mixture of air and crankcase gases then exits, often via another simple baffle, screen, or mesh to exclude oil mist, through the PCV valve and into the intake manifold.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] On some PCV systems, this oil baffling takes place in a discrete replaceable part called the 'oil separator'.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Aftermarket products sold to add an external oil baffling system to vehicles, which were not originally installed with them, are commonly known as "oil catch tanks".
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The PCV valve controls the flow of crankcase gases entering the intake system.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] At idle, with almost closed throttle, the manifold vacuum is high, which would draw in a large quantity of crankcase gases, causing the engine to run too lean.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The PCV valve closes when the manifold vacuum is high, restricting the quantity of crankcase gases entering the intake system.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] When the engine is under load or operating at higher RPM, a higher quantity of blow-by gases are produced.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The intake manifold vacuum, with wide open throttle, is lower in these conditions, which causes the PCV valve to open and the crankcase gases flow to the intake system.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The greater flow rate of intake air during these conditions means that a greater quantity of blow-by gases can be added to the intake system without compromising the operation of the engine.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The opening of the PCV valve during these conditions also compensates for the intake system being less effective at drawing crankcase gases into the intake system.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] A second function of the PCV valve is to act as a flame arrester and check valve to prevent positive pressure from the intake system from entering the crankcase.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This can happen on turbocharged engines or when a backfire takes place, and the positive pressure could damage the crankcase seals and gaskets, or even cause a crankcase explosion.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The PCV valve therefore closes when positive pressure is present, to prevent it from reaching the crankcase.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The crankcase air outlet, where the PCV valve is located, is generally placed as far as possible from the crankcase breather.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] For example, the breather and outlet are frequently on opposite valve covers on a V engine, or on opposite ends of the valve cover on an inline engine.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The PCV valve is often, but not always, placed at the valve cover; it may be located anywhere between the crankcase air outlet and the inlet manifold.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The PCV valve gains an even more important function in increasingly popular forced induction applications.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Excessive crankcase pressure will not only occur due to blow-by gases escaping past the piston rings but can also be introduced when positive pressure from the intake manifold makes its way into the crankcase.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] As previously mentioned, in vehicles with forced induction systems such as turbochargers or superchargers, the engine's intake manifold experiences positive pressure under load.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This differs from naturally aspirated applications where the intake manifold will remain in vacuum while under load.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Thus, when a forced induction engine is under load, the intake manifold can no longer be used to draw blow-by gasses out of the crankcase and will instead begin to exacerbate the problem by increasing crankcase pressure.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] It is then the job of the PCV valve to isolate the intake manifold and crankcase when the intake manifold is pressurized and allow the flow of blow-by gases out of the crankcase when the intake manifold is under vacuum.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] In addition to this added role, in boosted applications cylinder pressures are much higher, and consequently, more blow-by gases are pushed into the crankcase thus making a fully functional PCV system all the more important.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Carbon build-up in the intake manifold will occur when blow-by gases are allowed to permanently contaminate the intake air because of a failing PCV system.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Carbon build-up or oil sludge from blow-by gases on intake valves are usually not a problem in port injected engines.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This is due to the fact that the fuel hits the intake valves on the way to the combustion chamber, allowing the detergents in the fuel to keep them clean.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] However, carbon build-up on intake valves is a problem for engines with direct injection only, as the fuel is injected directly into the combustion chamber.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Because of this, fuel system cleaners or fuel additives added to the tank will not help clean these deposits.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Methods for cleaning these deposits include spraying cleaner through the intake or direct media blasting of the intake valves.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Two-stroke engines which use crankcase compression do not require a crankcase ventilation system, since all of the gases within the crankcase are then fed into the combustion chamber.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Many small four-stroke engines such as lawn mower engines and electricity generators simply use a draught tube connected to the intake system.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] The draught tube routes all blow-by gases back into the intake mixture and is usually located between the air filter and carburetor.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] Dry sump engines in some drag racing cars use scavenging pumps to extract oil and gases from the crankcase.
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] A separator removes the oil, then the gases are fed into the exhaust system via a venturi tube..
[src:crankcase-ventilation-system/crankcase-ventilation-system] This system maintains a small amount of vacuum in the crankcase and minimises the amount of oil in the engine that could potentially spill onto the racetrack.
